Text.Value: That's worth some coin. And my thanks.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - The character hands over money to the player.

Text.Value: This job you mentioned - what's involved?
You're a friend of the Zhent now - that's worth something in Baldur's Gate.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wryly amused, sizing us up - we made some powerful friends in helping her.

Text.Value: What makes that cargo so important?
Leave.
Bring them back alive if you can. Failing that, get me that shipment. Unopened.

EditorData.NodeContext: Giving orders, conveying grim urgency.

Text.Value: Yeah? Got business to conduct, so if you ain't helping you can toddle off.

EditorData.NodeContext: Disinterested - we refused to take on a job for her and so she has no use for us.

Text.Value: I have news of your missing people.
Leave.
Good luck with that. I don't want to get involved.
Spend your coin and be on your way. But be quick about it - we're blowing this place soon.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging - we can suit ourselves but if we're not going to be of use, we can do whatever trading we want and get out.

Text.Value: Looks like we can be friends after all.

EditorData.NodeContext: Reassessing us - we've gone from useless to useful in her eyes.

Text.Value: I'm afraid they won't coming back.
I've changed my mind. I'll take the job.
Then someone kidnapped a duke - right on our bloody doorstep.

EditorData.NodeContext: Vague disgust - she sees herself as a professional, and is disdainful of those who can't run similarly efficient operations.

Text.Value: Assuming we make it back there in one piece.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sardonic, considering the dangerous path ahead.

Text.Value: All you need to know is that I'm willing to pay a hideous sum to get it back - unopened.

EditorData.NodeContext: Laying the job out very clearly, not going to be pushed into any more detail

Text.Value: Give her the flask you found inside the chest.

EditorData.logicalname: Player tries to give her the flask.

Text.Value: Any luck finding my people?

EditorData.NodeContext: Straight to the point - when last we spoke she gave us a job, and that's all she's interested in.
EditorData.logicalname: Agreed to find Rugan/Olly, haven't yet

Text.Value: What's this job you mentioned?
I saved Rugan. He'll be along soon.
You... lost it. Funny, that - you just lost a heap of coin too.

EditorData.NodeContext: Repeating as if she doesn't quite understand. Then emphasising to us just how serious this is, frustrated we've come back looking for a reward for a job we half-assed.

Text.Value: Failure creates debt. And debt requires payment. But he'll live.
A job? You were ready to kill me a moment ago.
I found a pair that sound like your men - being swarmed by gnolls.

EditorData.logicalname: Saw agents, walked away OR fallback for only Olly survived

Text.Value: Time was, no one dared touch a caravan bearing our colours.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stating how notorious her group is, how serious it is that someone attacked a shipment

Text.Value: I was glad to see Rugan, until he told me he lost the shipment.
Find whoever did this and remind them why.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim - giving us permission to hurt whoever hurt her group.

Text.Value: Still am, as it goes. Take it as a mark of respect.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging, unconcerned - she's ready to kill anyone at any moment, it's not personal.

Text.Value: Well I'll give you a hint, shall I? They ain't down here. On your way.

EditorData.NodeContext: Friendly turning sarcastic

Text.Value: I found them. They're dead.
But right now, I reckon we're better off friends than enemies. You interested or not?

EditorData.NodeContext: Getting back on track, not interested in our concerns - just the job at hand.

Text.Value: Some of our people are missing - more importantly, so is their cargo.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim - we're getting to the heart of the matter. She's fairly unflappable but this job is extremely important.

Text.Value: I don't plan on it being us.
Rubble? What are you planning to do?
Welcome to the family. Don't get comfortable - that shipment's wanted in Baldur's Gate.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry, vaguely amused, considering us - we impressed her enough that she recruited us instead of killing us, but we still have a job to do.

Text.Value: Not many can talk their way into a Zhentarim outpost.
If you've got coin to spend and problems to solve, the Zhent will relieve you of both.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stating it simply - her group are mercenaries, there's nothing complicated about it

Text.Value: I already found them. They're dead.
Leave.
What're you jawing at me for, recruit? You've got work to do.

EditorData.NodeContext: Expectant - she spared our life so we could carry out an important task for her. So why aren't we doing it?

Text.Value: That's Zhent business, not yours.
You've already brought me bad news - tell me you've got something better this time.

EditorData.NodeContext: When last we spoke we told her her men were dead - but she's more concerned with the shipment that was with them. She's waiting on word from us.
EditorData.logicalname: Told her Rugan/Olly dead, didn't give shipment

Text.Value: I'm just here to trade - I have my own concerns.
Good. Reckon you won't find it here, though.

EditorData.NodeContext: Blunt, disinterested - if we haven't found what she needs, she's not interested.

Text.Value: But today I'm offering work, not looking for it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bringing us back to the topic at hand, no longer interested in indulging our curiosity

Text.Value: I don't want to get caught up in any of this.
Beshaba's black bones, you bloody found it. Funny thing, though - I swear I told you not to open it.

EditorData.AnimationTags: *DUPE* The player is handing over the unopened chest taken from the cave. <Murat>
EditorData.NodeContext: First half is surprise and relief that we completed a crucial job - second half is her taking on irrevocable edge after realising we've broken the terms of the deal, though - and now she has to kill us.
EditorData.StateChangeTags: Taking and holding the unopened chest from the player.

Text.Value: What's so important about this cargo?
Lot of explosives. Planning a war?
I have news of your missing people.
Didn't think you'd get your coin based on spinning some tale, did you?

EditorData.NodeContext: Vaguely chiding - we told her we'd do a job, and she's not going to be giviing us a penny until we complete it.

Text.Value: Well?

EditorData.NodeContext: Expectant - there's no reason for us not to be getting to the point.

Text.Value: And still sealed? You're a godsdamned wonder. Here's your coin.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - The character is holding and checking the unopened chest, he ends up handing money to the player.
EditorData.NodeContext: Checking the box, relieved and impressed that we've finished the job perfectly.

Text.Value: Sounds shady. I'd rather not get involved.
Maybe not now, no. But that'll change once the council gets involved. They'll want heads to roll.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dismissing our point - she has more experience in these matters than we do.

Text.Value: Find them. Keep them alive if you can. Failing that, just bring that shipment back. Unopened.

EditorData.NodeContext: Giving orders, conveying grim urgency.

Text.Value: I'm still looking.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Player has never interacted with chest. Enables 14fedd62-c2e7-8d4a-4b01-f5c557cb4f53

Text.Value: Fine. What's the job?
We're getting out - just one last loose end to take care of. Help me and I'll make it worth your while.

EditorData.NodeContext: Firm - the matter is settled, so are we going to be useful to her or not?

Text.Value: Some of our people are missing - more importantly, so is their cargo. They were in a caravan coming from the east.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim - we're getting to the heart of the matter. She's fairly unflappable but this job is extremely important.

Text.Value: Rubble? What are you planning to do?
Leave without mentioning the cargo.
And making a small fortune ain't one of them?

EditorData.NodeContext: Skeptical that our goals are any more important or lucrative than the job she's offering.

Text.Value: Our trader can show you some of our more exotic items, now - but don't delay. This place is likely to be rubble soon.
Here's your coin, as promised.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - The character hands over money to the player.

Text.Value: Beshaba's black bones, you did it!

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - The player is handing over the unopened chest taken from the cave.
EditorData.NodeContext: Actual surprise and relief - her survival depends on this shipment and we've recovered it.
EditorData.StateChangeTags: Taking and holding the unopened chest from the player.

Text.Value: We're the finest mercenaries on the Coast.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not a boast - just a simple statement of fact.

Text.Value: Give her the chest.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Only visible if player has opened chest in inventory.
EditorData.logicalname: Player tries to give her the opened chest.

Text.Value: Couldn't you just be a professional? Do as you're told, no questions asked? Like so:

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim, frustrated - why can't anyone around her just to their job properly. The 'like so' is her about to order her men to kill us, demonstrating how one follows orders.

Text.Value: Leave.
Give her the chest.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Only visible if unopened chest is in inventory.
EditorData.logicalname: Player gives her the sealed chest.

Text.Value: Actual professionals are rare - you ever want more work, come see me in the Gate.

EditorData.NodeContext: She looks on us as an equal - she usually views those she works with as messy or inferior.

Text.Value: Actually, hells with this - the day I've had? You just lost your life too.

EditorData.NodeContext: Gives up trying to contain her anger at how badly we've messed up the job.

Text.Value: You... opened the shipment.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - The player is giving the flask to the character.
EditorData.NodeContext: Mute, neutral - she's not surprised by much, but opening this shipment means we've killed her and all her men.
EditorData.StateChangeTags: The character is now holding the flask.

Text.Value: I saved them. They'll be along soon.
You've killed me. You've bloody killed us all. Damned if I won't return the favour.

EditorData.NodeContext: Beat between sentences. Grim towards the end, deciding she's going to take us down with her.

Text.Value: Lads! Kill him.
Lads! Kill her.
Lads! Kill them.

EditorData.NodeContext: Louder, leads to violence.

Text.Value: The Flaming Fist will want someone to blame, and I don't plan to leave anything pointing our way.

EditorData.NodeContext: She's disdainful of the Flaming Fist, a rival organisation known for corruption and inefficiency.

Text.Value: Here's your coin, as promised.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - The character hands over money to the player.

Text.Value: I'm offering hard coin, not idle answers.

EditorData.NodeContext: Annoyed at our probing - she's offering us a job for a lot of money, and that's all we need to know.

Text.Value: I owe you one for saving my people. The Zhentarim look out for their own - even if it's Rugan.
You did me a service - doesn't make you one of us.
That's worth some coin. And my thanks.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - The character hands over money to the player.

Text.Value: Doesn't sound like a group I want to get involved with.
Then I'm in your debt - or will be, once I see him and his cargo.

EditorData.NodeContext: Neutral - not unfriendly but we're telling her something too good to be true and until she sees evidence she's not interested in dealing with us

Text.Value: I had your cargo, but I lost it.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Only visible if player had chest or flask in inventory and no longer does.
EditorData.logicalname: Player had but lost or sold flask and chest

Text.Value: The Fist already know you're here. They just don't care.
Leave.
Someone kidnapped a duke - right on our bloody doorstep. The Flaming Fist will need someone to blame.
Pity we didn't have you on the job from the start.
Good. Backtrack along the road to the east and look for a wagon. Bodies. The usual.

EditorData.NodeContext: Satisfied - and immediately down to business.

Text.Value: I'd rather know who I'd be working for first - the Zhentarim?
I could use someone with your skills. Interested in a job?

EditorData.NodeContext: Making an offer, feeling us out

Text.Value: We can provide you with anything - for a price.

EditorData.NodeContext: Again, not boastful - just a statement of fact. They're merchants who have no scruples about what they sell or who to.

Text.Value: Then I'm much obliged - or I will be, once I see them and their cargo.

EditorData.NodeContext: Neutral - not unfriendly but we're telling her something too good to be true and until she sees evidence she's not interested in dealing with us

Text.Value: Gods damn it. What about the shipment?

EditorData.NodeContext: We've given her bad news, but her mens' lives are secondary to her actual goal - she's most urgent about the shipment

Text.Value: Wait, so what are you: merchants or mercenaries?
All right - I'll do it.
I'm still looking.
That depends - what is it?
Cleaning up. We had a steady operation going here.

EditorData.NodeContext: Speaking about something distasteful - their operation was running smoothly until another organisation ruined it for them.

Text.Value: Backtrack along the road to the east. They were travelling with a wagon.

EditorData.NodeContext: Short, terse - a commander briefing a subordinate who will obey

Text.Value: It's gold I'm offering, not a marriage bond.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Murat - Player is shaking his head saying no.
EditorData.NodeContext: Scornful of our moral objections - she's offering us a simple job

Synopsis: Zarys has allowed the player to enter the Zhentarim hideout - either because we won her trust or she needs our help finding her missing agents.
